Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/13947: A double click on a name should stop at a dash
Date: Sat, 10 Aug 2013 10:56:26 -0400

 I think that the proper thing to do is to distinguish words from
 sexprs, and clarify that a double-click does the latter.  (IIRC, the
 function names also have "word"s in them, which is bad choice.
 Consider also the fact that there are word-* functions that actually
 work on human words, so the terminology is inconsistent.)
 
 
 Three hours ago, Robby Findler wrote:
 > I see. Thank you for clarifying that this was a request. I
 > misunderstood your original message.
 > 
 > I found this (old) copy of the human interface guidelines that
 > suggests that DrRacket's current behavior is the right one:
 > 
 > http://dropbox.scripting.com/dave/misc/appleHumanInterfaceGuidelines.pdf
 > 
 > with the possible exception that hyphen should be considered a word
 > separator.  Indeed, some 10 or 15 years ago, I believe DrRacket did
 > that, but I found that making hyphen as a non-separator worked
 > better, since I usually wanted to get an entire identifier when I
 > double click on it (as an identifier is more logically a "word" in a
 > Racket program, IMO). So it has been that way for a long time and I
 > don't think we should change it now, as many people are, I presume,
 > used to this behavior.
 > 
 > Meanwhile, you can control how double-clicking works by making your
 > keybindings file. Below is one that does what you want, I
 > believe. (I've put more code than is strictly necessary, so you can
 > maybe make other tweaks.)
 
 -- 
           ((lambda (x) (x x)) (lambda (x) (x x)))          Eli Barzilay:
                     http://barzilay.org/                   Maze is Life!
